  {panel}

The mail archive page would be more usefull if it could be managed as a mailing list.

People in one or several Confluence group should be able to send email to the email archive address. The received mails (on this address) are dispatched to other people in configured groups. The peopler receiving the emails should in turn be able to answer it (the resulting mail will be dispatched, and so on).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4690].
  {panel}

It would be nice if the {jiraissues} macro (or variation of) could display a form field on the page into which a search term or phrase was entered by the viewer, and upon submit, a search query was passed to jira and results displayed.

It would be nice to configure the type of query it would pass ... perhaps in the form on an xml link.
- Configure by standard filters .... project name, issue type, status, etc ...

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This bug report is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding bug report|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4647].
  {panel}

Is there any way to create a blue, underlined heading like the one that says "Welcome to Confluence" on the start page? I would like to replace the welcome message, but without loosing the visual style of the default message.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4645].
  {panel}

The ability to filter the output of various macros by label would be highly benificial - you could list all the children of a page that are labelled "Meeting" or "Report", you could show the last 5 blogposts of the label "PressRelease".

The macros I have in mind are the blog-posts and children macros, however there may be others which would benifit from such filtering.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4637].
  {panel}

We are starting to use our copy of Confluence *a lot* at StatPro.  I'm not sure if you are aware of it, but your mail capabilities are the thing that differentiate your product from most other Wiki's...why?  Because in most organisations people can't be bothered to log in and add pages.  However it is easy for people to simply cc emails to the Wiki.  As a result, the mail section of the Wiki is now *FULL* of amazing information.  It would be amazing if an user with editing rights could look at a particular mail and then convert it into a normal wiki page.  This way the wiki can be beautifully maintained and mails can then start to form part of the main body content of a space.  This would be a truly great feature.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4632].
  {panel}

It would be nice to add support for simple spreadsheet functionality to tables so that calculations can be carried out on cell values within the table.

This could be built as a macro or as an extension to existing table functionality.

B

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4625].
  {panel}

Often you want to work with data stored in tables in different contexts. Being able to export your table data into a CSV file would be fantastic.

We should also test copying and pasting this reworked data back into the table in the WYSIWYG editor - assuming the number of columns and rows remains static.

This will also address the currenlty missing ability to carry out simple spreadsheet like functionality on table data within Confluence.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4617].
  {panel}

Currently the only way to exchange information between macros is to set attributes on the request. Since the request is not always available to a macro, this is a bad idea. 

Eg. if a macro like the dynamic task list outputs javascript code, you only want it to output the code once, even though there might be more than one task lists on the page. Therefore we will need to communicate between different macro calls using a boolean flag to detect whether the repeated tags have been outputted already and to skip it.

Allowing to set arbitrary attributes on the renderContext would solve this problem.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4616].
  {panel}

The "confluence-administrators" super-users group is a major source of confusion. We should remove the isSuperUser() check entirely.

There will need to be some way for users with the regular admin permission to change perms on spaces (so spaces that nobody can get to can be recovered) -- uses of this power should be logged.

It should probably remain possible to grant permissions that allow access to all content for special administrative use like exports, automation, etc.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4613].
  {panel}

Confluence has a \{quote} macro, but as everyone knows from email, the correct way to quote text is with '>'s  :)

This would be of particular use in JIRA, where we could have a Bugzilla-like 'quote this comment' link inserting >-prefixed comments, which would look acceptable in both text and html email notifications.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4609].
  {panel}

Even though there is autocompletion it is often easier to choose labels by looking at what labels exist. It could therefore be helpful if it was possible to open a pop-up window with a heat map of all labels when in "Add Labels" mode.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4608].
  {panel}

Would be great if there was a macro to displayed the heat map with all labels (or all labels used in a space).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4600].
  {panel}

Instead of having "/createrssfeed.action?" we should consider to map something like "/rss.xml?" to the createrssfeed action.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4599].
  {panel}

A customer has requested the ability to embed JSR-168 compliant portlets in a Confluence page with SSO. It would also be useful to produce any Confluence page as a portlet that can be consumed by an external application.

http://developers.sun.com/prodtech/portalserver/reference/techart/jsr168/index.html

Java Specification Request (JSR) 168 enables interoperability among portlets and portals. This specification defines a set of APIs for portlets and addresses standardization for preferences, user information, portlet requests and responses, deployment packaging, and security.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4591].
  {panel}

Do avoid uncorrect emails, it would be great if Confluence would mail a user signup verification page with an activation link back to confluence.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4582].
  {panel}

Currently the only means to link to a mail item is using their ID. The problem with this, is that all these links are broken when the space is imported into another Confluence instance (all content imported from a space export are given new ID's to prevent ID collision).

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *Confluence Cloud*. Using *Confluence Server*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CONFSERVER-4580].
  {panel}

The PermissionCheckDispatcher is far too slow to handle large numbers of permission checks on a page. 

Why? The PermissionCheckDispatcher runs its permission checks by generating a mock xwork action and sending it through the xwork stack for processing. It is picked up by an interceptor that checks if the action is allowed, and then returns. The reason this is so slow is the overhead of the action being passed through the xwork stack. One permission check is okay. When you have 700 spaces listed on one page, 700 permission checks are way to slow.

The PermissionHelper uses the new Permission delegate system which is much quicker.

